essures, theological, social, and, not least, aesthetic.Key FeaturesDivided into 3 sections, Inspiration and Theory, Art and Architecture, and LiteratureGenerously illustratedCovers aesthetic interpretations of specific biblical books; of the Hebrew and Christian Bibles as a whole; the transmission of biblical texts; various bindings and illustrations of Bibles – in response to pressures as diverse as Islamic craftsmanship and the English ReformationIncludes biblical influences on poetry, painting, church architecture, decoration, and stained glass; on poetry, hymns, novels, plays, and fantasy literatureSpans the earliest days of the Christian era to the present  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aArts in the Bible. 0aChristian art and symbolism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Reference.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAston, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBear, Bethany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielby, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurdon, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Mordechai Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Phillip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErskine-Hill, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorak, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a